  <h3>2014 Layer Hen Death Interval in the U.S.</h3>
  <p><sup><%= number_with_delimiter data.slaughter.chickens.layers.total_2014 %> hens</sup>/<sub>year</sub> * <sup>year</sup>/<sub><%= number_with_delimiter SECONDS_PER_YEAR.to_i %> seconds</sub> = <sup><%= "%.2f" % (data.slaughter.chickens.layers.total_2014/SECONDS_PER_YEAR) %> hens</sup>/<sub>second</sub> = <sup>1 hen</sup>/<sub><%= "%.2f" % (SECONDS_PER_YEAR/data.slaughter.chickens.layers.total_2014) %> seconds</sub></p>
</div>

<div class="padded z-depth-1">
  <h2>Number of Male Chicks Hatched/Culled Per Year</h2>

  <p>It can be assumed that for each layer pullet added to the flock, a male chick was hatched. That is, there were around <%= number_with_delimiter data.slaughter.chickens.layers.male_chicks.total_2014 %> male chicks hatched in 2014 (see <strong>Total Number Slaughtered, Lost, and Added &mdash; United States: 2013 and 2014</strong> above), and it can be assumed that nearly 100% of those were culled.</p>

  <h3>2014 Male Chick Cull Interval in the U.S.</h3>
  <p><sup><%= number_with_delimiter data.slaughter.chickens.layers.male_chicks.total_2014 %> chicks</sup>/<sub>year</sub> * <sup>year</sup>/<sub><%= number_with_delimiter SECONDS_PER_YEAR.to_i %> seconds</sub> = <sup><%= "%.2f" % (data.slaughter.chickens.layers.male_chicks.total_2014/SECONDS_PER_YEAR) %> chicks</sup>/<sub>second</sub> = <sup>1 chick</sup>/<sub><%= "%.2f" % (SECONDS_PER_YEAR/data.slaughter.chickens.layers.male_chicks.total_2014) %> seconds</sub></p>
</div>

</div>